defaultThe structure and governance of banks in defaultNorthern Irelanddefault&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultThere are clearly significant differences in the banking structure in 
defaultNorthern Ireland
default compared to Great Britain (GB). Of the four main banks – 
defaultUlster
default, First Trust, Bank of Ireland and 
defaultDanske
default – three are not UK-owned. First Trust (as part of Allied Irish Banks) and Bank of Ireland are headquartered in 
defaultDublin
default, whilst 
defaultDanske
default is Danish-owned. Some large GB banks such as HSBC and Barclays only have a comparatively small presence in 
defaultNorthern Ireland
default. The strong link between the banking system in 
defaultNorthern Ireland
default and the 
defaultRepublic
default of 
defaultIreland
default presents particular challenges, given the difficulties faced by the Irish economy in recent years. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Chancellor has made clear that the link between our financial systems, which is most pronounced in 
defaultNorthern Ireland
default, was a strong factor in the Government’s decision to provide a bilateral loan to the 
defaultRepublic
default of 
defaultIreland
default.  
default&#xa0;
defaultThe 
defaultUK
default signed an agreement for a bilateral loan of £3.2 billion in December 2010, as part of an €67.5 billion international financial assistance package for 
defaultIreland
default. The 
defaultGovernment expects the loan to be repaid in full and with interest.  
defaultSweden
default and 
defaultDenmark
default have also provided bilateral loans to 
defaultIreland
default. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe loan is disbursed in eight tranches of £4
default03 
defaultmillion, subject to the completion of quarterly programme reviews. The first seven tranches have been disbursed to date.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe conditions of the bilateral loan also made clear that the funding was subject to the Iri
defaultsh Government not amending its r
defaultestr
defaultucturing p
defaultlan in a way that would have a material adverse financial impact on the 
defaultUK
default operations of Anglo Irish bank, Allied Irish Banks or the Bank of Ireland. 
default 
defaultAs the Chancellor 
defaultsaid when the Loans to Ireland Act was debated in the House of Commons
default, providing the bilateral loan has enabled 
defaultthe Government
default to be part of discussions about the restructuring plan and its impact on the UK subsidiaries of banks which have significant presence in Northern Ireland.
defaultThe National Asset Management Agency (NAMA) 
defaultis one of 
defaulta number of initiatives taken by the Irish Government to address the crisis in Irish banking. 
defaultNAMA was formally established on 21 December 2009. Five institutions (and their subsidiaries) applied to join the NAMA scheme and were designated as participating institutions in February 2010: Allied Irish Banks; Bank of Ireland; Anglo Irish Bank; Irish Nationwide Building Society; and EBS Building Society.
defaultThe first phase of NAMA’s operation involved the acquisition and transfer of over €71 billion in loan assets involving 850 debtors and more than 11,000 individual loans collateralised by 16,000 individual properties. Approximately two-thirds of the assets backing those loans are located in 
defaultIreland
default and most of the remainder is located in the 
defaultUK
default with smaller concentrations in the 
defaultUS
default and throughout continental 
defaultEurope
default.
defaultOn the proposal of the Irish Minister for Finance, NAMA set up a Northern Ireland Advisory Committee. Its purpose is to advise the Board in relation to strategy for 
defaultNorthern Ireland
default assets. 
defaultApproximately 3
default per cent 
defaultof NAMAs property profile is 
defaultlocated in Northern Ireland; 36 per cent
default Dublin; 18
default per cent
default Rest of Ireland; 21
default per cent London; 12 per cent
default Rest of GB; and 10
default per cent
default Rest of World.
defaultIts portfolio i
defaultn NI is worth €1.3 billion or 4 per cent 
defaultof its total acquisition value of
default €31.8billion. Approximately 70 per cent
default of its NI portfolio is completed property and income producing. By 
defaultthe end of 
defaultMarch 2013, asset sales approved stood at £86.6 million. By the same time, it had approved £123 million in new advances to NI debtors.
default NAMAs stated approach has been to encourage a phased and orderly realisation of its assets in 
defaultNorthern Ireland
default.
