defaultThe possible breakdefault-defaultup of RBS/Ulster Bankdefault 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Government recognises that RBS, including Ulster Bank, remains weighed down by too many poor assets. The Chancellor announced in his Mansion House speech on 19 June that the Treasury would be examining the case for breaking RBS up and establishing a Bad Bank.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Government welcomed the input of the Northern Ireland Executive on the future of RBS, conveyed through its former and current finance ministers, Sammy Wilson and Simon Hamilton. The views of the 
defaultNorthern Ireland
default business community were also considered following on from representations by the Secretary of State for 
defaultNorthern Ireland
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultOn 1 November 2013, RBS announced that it was committing to a new direction for the bank, in order for it to restructure and boost the British and Irish economies. RBS 
defaultwill 
defaultcreate an internal 
defaultbad bank 
defaultand £9 billion of Ulster Bank assets will be transferred into this new structure.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Chancellor recently stated that the Government, RBS and the Bank of England are all in agreement on the direction that RBS is heading. 
defaultRBS will focus on its core 
defaultUK
default business
default. 
defaultIt will sell off more of its overseas operations and 
defaultcontinue to reduce 
defaultits investment bank, so it has more capital to support lending to the 
defaultUK
default economy. RBS 
defaulthas also committed
default to becoming the best small business bank in 
defaultthe 
defaultUK
default. 
default&#xa0;
defaultRBS’s operations in 
defaultNorthern Ireland
default 
defaultthrough Ulster Bank, which also operates in 
defaultIreland
default,
default remain an important part of RBS’s core operations and the new direction the 
defaultbank has announced. However, a sustainable operating model needs to be found for it so that it can play its full part in delivering 
defaultsupport to both economies
default. To achieve this, RBS has announced that Ulster Bank will be part of 
defaultits full business review, reporting
default in February 2014, with the aim of identifying a long term viable and sustainable business model
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultIt is in the 
defaultUK
default’s interest that 
defaultIreland
default has a successful economy and a stable banking system. 
defaultIt is therefore important that Ulster Bank is in a position to support the economy in both 
defaultNorthern Ireland
default 
defaultand 
defaultthe 
defaultRepublic
default of 
defaultIreland
default, through new lending and generating new business.
default&#xa0;
defaultRBS's 1st November announcement is a positive step in this direction since it will see Ulster Bank remain as an important part of the RBS group, with its balance sheet strengthened by the transfer of problem assets to the internal bad bank. Developing a sustainable business model for Ulster Bank which is capable of
default&#xa0;
defaultsupporting its cost base may involve some difficult decisions following the forthcoming review, but should ultimately leave Ulster 
defaultBank 
defaultas a stronger bank better able to support lending to business.
