default       defaultLack of effectiveness of national initiatives to help aid economic recoverydefault&#xa0;
defaultUK
default wide lending schemes set-up by the Government play an important role in providing credit to businesses and individuals in 
defaultNorthern Ireland
default. Ulster Bank 
defaulthas 
defaultannounced that it ha
defaults
default approved 
defaultnearly £8
default0 million of loans through the Funding for Lending Scheme
default (FLS)
default, helping 
defaultover 5
default00 businesses in 
defaultNorthern Ireland
default. FLS has 
defaultenabled Ulster Bank to establish a new Funding for Lending deal, under which customers will not be charged an arrangement fee for any new loans drawn under the scheme.  
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Enterprise Finance Guarantee
default Scheme (EFG) has provided 195
default loans
default amounting to £27.66 million
default 
defaultin 
defaultNorthern Ireland
default since May 2010
default. 
defaultIn addition to these national schemes, the Northern Ireland Executive has its own £100 million ‘Access to Finance Strategy’, which incorporates a number of smaller schemes designed to boost lending. 
default&#xa0;
defaultHowever, the Government accepts that 
defaultUK
default wide schemes to boost lending have not always been as effective in 
defaultNorthern Ireland
default as they have been elsewhere in the 
defaultUK
default. The take-up of EFG is lower in 
defaultNorthern Ireland
default than anywhere else in the 
defaultUK
default. The framework we set out in 
defaultBuilding a Prosperous and United Community
default is intended to provide a mechanism to ensure that there is sufficient monitoring and evaluation of national schemes to ensure that they work more effectively in 
defaultNorthern Ireland
default in future.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe package also makes specific proposals on improving existing schemes to increase their impact in 
defaultNorthern Ireland
default. We have fulfilled our commitment in the package to extend the Start-up Loans scheme to 
defaultNorthern Ireland
default. Delivery partners for this scheme have been agreed and the first Start-up Loans have already been made to young entrepreneurs with seven loans approved to the value of £30,000 by the end of October 2013. The package includes a commitment to work to ensure that 
defaultNorthern Ireland
default benefits from a pilot extension to the Enterprise Finance Guarantee Scheme, aimed at addressing loan affordability. We have also committed to continuing to work with the remaining banks to encourage their participation in the Funding for Lending Scheme. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIt is important to note that improving the effectiveness of these schemes cannot be achieved by the Government alone. We would welcome the Committee’s analysis of how banks in 
defaultNorthern Ireland
default are promoting, marketing and championing schemes such as 
defaultEFG,
default and the extent to which the remaining banks are proactively seeking to address any issues holding them back from joining the Funding for Lending Scheme. 
